ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: 12 Mar 2010
Source: SFGate [edited]
<http://articles.sfgate.com/2010-03-12/news/18386905_1_moth-napa-county-quarantineInvasion>


Invasive moth threatens wine grape crop
---------------------------------------
A huge swath of wine country [California], including vineyards where
some of the world's best grapes are grown, was quarantined this week
after an invasive moth was discovered.

The European grapevine moth has already destroyed at least one
vineyard's harvest and damaged other prime vineyards in the Napa
Valley, prompting the California Department of Food and Agriculture
to place under quarantine 162 square miles of land.

"This is a serious threat to grape growing throughout California,"
said Greg Clark, assistant agricultural commissioner, Napa County.
"We don't want it to become established because we've seen the severe
damage this pest can do." The grape-gobbling pest has long been the
scourge of winemakers in Europe, but the discovery of moth larvae in
a Napa Valley vineyard in September [2009] marked the 1st time the
insect had been seen in the US.

The quarantine covers 2 areas, the larger of which is in the heart of
the Napa Valley and reaches just over the Sonoma County line. The
smaller pocket includes parts of the city of Napa and stretches into
Solano County. The quarantine means agricultural commissioners will
regulate the harvest, shipping and handling of certain fruits and
plants, including grapes, persimmons, olives, pomegranates and kiwi.

Authorities are also asking property owners not to remove the
designated plants and crops from their lands, though produce may be
consumed on the properties. Inspectors are working with growers,
nurseries, landscapers and other agricultural workers to limit the
spread of the moth and enforce the regulations. Clark said 715 traps
that draw the insects to sticky strips have been set up in the
quarantine areas and there are plans to set more in growing regions
throughout the state.

[Byline: By Peter Fimrite]

