Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The European grapevine moth, _Lobesia botrana_ (_Tortricidae_) is
found throughout Europe, North and West Africa, the Middle East, and
eastern Russia. Besides grapevine, it has also been reported on
olive, blackberry, gooseberry, black and red currant, cherry, plum,
persimmon, kiwifruit, pomegranate and a number of wild hosts. The
moth is nocturnal and can fly several hundred meters looking for dry
places.

The adult moth is approximately 6-8 mm long and has a lifespan of 1
to 3 weeks, depending on climatic conditions. Unlike other common
vineyard torticids which lay eggs in overlapping masses, eggs of_
L.botrana_ are laid singly under the bark of the vine stem or in the
supporting posts, with a mean of 80 to 140 eggs per female laid over
about 6 days. Pupae overwinter in diapause (resting state) in cocoons
under the bark, in soil cracks, or on trellis posts. Adults emerge
when air temperatures exceed a threshold of 10 degrees Celsius [50
deg F] for a period of 10 to 12 days. The 2nd generation larvae feed
on green berries leaving only skin and seeds. The 3rd generation
larvae cause the greatest damage by webbing and feeding inside
berries and within bunches, which become contaminated with frass
[excrement]. Feeding damages the berries and exposes them to
infection by various fungal pathogens.

Control measures are targeted at the 2nd generation because of the
prolonged emergence of the 1st generation and possible re-infestation
from untreated neighbouring vineyards. However, treatment of the 1st
generation is used for high populations or area wide control. Under
California conditions, control of both 1st and 2nd generations may be
warranted, given that this is a newly introduced pest.

Insecticides used are less effective after bunch closure. Several
reduced-risk insecticides are registered for use in grapes to control
tortricid larvae. These include insect growth regulators, spinosyns
(fungal fermentation products) and _Bacillus thuringiensis_. Mating
disruption has been studied in Europe and has proven most effective
when moth populations are low and when applied to large areas. Since
this is a newly reported pest, no _L.botrana_ pheromone mating
disruption products are currently registered in the US.

